comment.undefined: GNU Guix is a functional package manager that facilitates the creation of reproducible and declarative software environments. It allows users to define complete software environments that can be shared and replicated across different systems, enhancing reproducibility in software deployment.

MongoDB is a document-oriented NoSQL database that stores data in flexible, JSON-like documents. It offers scalability and flexibility for handling large volumes of unstructured or semi-structured data, making it suitable for modern application development.

Apptainer is an open-source container platform. It enables users to create and run containers that encapsulate applications and their dependencies, ensuring portability and reproducibility across diverse computing systems.

BigDFT is an open-source electronic structure code based on density functional theory (DFT) that utilizes Daubechies wavelets as a computational basis. It is designed for ab initio simulations of materials and molecular systems, offering high precision and scalability for large-scale simulations.

AiiDA (Automated Interactive Infrastructure and Database for Computational Science) is an open-source Python framework for managing, preserving, and disseminating computational scientific workflows. It provides automated provenance tracking, data management, and workflow execution capabilities for high-throughput computational materials science.

X-window CRYstalline Structures and DENsities - A crystalline and molecular structure visualization program for displaying isosurfaces, contours, and atomic structures, with support for various quantum chemistry and solid-state physics codes.
Visual Molecular Dynamics - A molecular visualization program for displaying, animating, and analyzing large biomolecular systems using 3D graphics and built-in scripting for trajectory analysis.

An open-source, multi-platform data analysis and visualization application for large-scale scientific datasets, supporting various data formats and offering advanced visualization capabilities for finite element and computational fluid dynamics results.
Open Visualization Tool - A scientific visualization and analysis software for atomistic and particle simulation data, particularly suited for molecular dynamics and discrete element simulations.

Visualization for Electronic and STructural Analysis - A 3D visualization program for structural models, volumetric data such as electron/nuclear densities, and crystal morphologies, widely used in materials science and crystallography.

An open-source thermodynamic software for CALPHAD (CALculation of PHAse Diagrams) calculations, used for predicting phase equilibria and thermodynamic properties of multicomponent systems.
An open-source dislocation dynamics simulation code for modeling plastic deformation in crystalline materials through the collective motion of dislocations.
A finite element-based software suite for nonlinear material and structure analysis, particularly focused on thermomechanical simulations and advanced material behavior modeling.
A molecular simulation software for adsorption and diffusion in nanoporous materials, particularly metal-organic frameworks (MOFs) and zeolites, using Monte Carlo and molecular dynamics methods.
A workflow management system for computational materials science, designed to facilitate automated execution of complex simulation workflows and integration with high-performance computing resources.
A computational chemistry software designed for calculations on molecular systems of varying sizes, from small molecules to biomolecules and materials, using quantum mechanical and classical methods.
Large-scale Atomic/Molecular Massively Parallel Simulator. A classical molecular dynamics code for simulating materials, soft matter, and biological systems at the atomic scale.
A software package for training and applying high-dimensional neural network potentials for atomistic simulations, enabling accurate and efficient molecular dynamics with machine learning potentials.
An open-source computing platform for solving partial differential equations using the finite element method, with automated solution of variational problems and high-level Python interfaces.
A partial differential equation solver using the finite element method. Widely used for multiphysics simulations in fluid dynamics, structural mechanics, and electromagnetics.
A three-dimensional finite element mesh generator with built-in pre- and post-processing facilities, widely used for computational modeling in engineering and physics.
A software package for high-throughput analysis of porous materials and crystal structures, calculating geometric properties such as surface area, pore volume, and accessible channels.
A software package for polycrystal generation and meshing, designed to create representative volume elements of polycrystalline materials for finite element simulations.
A quantum chemistry and solid-state physics software package for atomistic simulations, particularly efficient for molecular dynamics simulations using mixed Gaussian and plane wave methods.

A software suite for electronic structure calculations based on density functional theory, using pseudopotentials and a plane wave or wavelet basis. Capable of treating metals, insulators, and molecules.
An extended tight-binding semi-empirical quantum chemistry program for efficiently calculating structures, properties, and reaction paths of molecular systems containing thousands of atoms.
A code for generating maximally-localized Wannier functions from electronic structure calculations, used for analyzing chemical bonding and calculating transport properties.
A density functional tight-binding code for efficient quantum mechanical calculations on large molecular and materials systems, offering a good balance between accuracy and computational cost.
An open-source plugin for free energy calculations in molecular dynamics, enabling enhanced sampling methods and analysis of molecular simulations across multiple MD codes.
An integrated suite of open-source codes for electronic-structure calculations and materials modeling at the nanoscale, based on density-functional theory, plane waves, and pseudopotentials.
